org.openbase.jul.schedule

Class Stopwatch

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.openbase.jul.schedule.Stopwatch

  • public class Stopwatch
extends Object
    Author:
    Divine Threepwood This class implements a general purpose stopwatch. This implementation should be thread safe.

    • Method Detail

      • reset

        public final void reset()
        This method resets the Stopwatch by clearing the internally stored start and end timestamps.

      • start

        public void start()
        This method starts the Stopwatch by setting the start timestamp.

      • restart

        public void restart()
        This method restarts the Stopwatch. Internally the reset() and start() methods are called.

      • getTime

        public long getTime()
             throws NotAvailableException
        This method returns the time interval between the start- and end timestamps. In case the the Stopwatch is still running, the elapsed time since Stopwatch start will be returned.
        Returns:
        the time interval in milliseconds.
        Throws:
        NotAvailableException - This exception will thrown in case the timer was never started.

      • isRunning

        public boolean isRunning()
        Method checks if the Stopwatch was started after reset. Even after calling the stop method the Stopwatch is still running until reset() is called.
        Returns:
        true if the Stopwatch was started.

      • stop

        public long stop()
          throws CouldNotPerformException
        This method stops the Stopwatch and returns the time result. The internal timestamps are not cleared by this method so the result can still queried by the getTime() method afterwards. Additionally this method can be called multiply times but only the last stop timestamp will be stored and handled by the getTime() method.
        Returns:
        the elapsed time interval since start.
        Throws:
        CouldNotPerformException - is thrown in case the Stopwatch was never started.
